│ corruption of the MemorySSA form where a memory definition   │
│ (`MemoryDef`) does not dominate one of its uses. This        │
│ typically happens when a code transformation, in this case,  │
│ `LoopRotate`, fails to correctly update the MemorySSA        │
│ structure.\n\n### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe core of  │
│ the problem lies in how `LoopRotate` handles MemorySSA       │
│ updates when transforming a loop. Loop rotation involves     │
│ duplicating the loop header and restructuring the control    │
│ flow. This process creates new basic blocks and moves        │
│ instructions, which necessitates careful updates to analyses │
│ like Dominator Tree, LoopInfo, and MemorySSA. The assertion  │
│ failure signals that after loop rotation, a `MemoryUse` is   │
│ linked to a `MemoryDef` that is no longer in a dominating    │
│ position, breaking a fundamental SSA invariant.\n\n### 2.    │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe provided `opt` log and          │
│ backtrace are crucial for diagnosis.\n- The backtrace        │
│ clearly pinpoints the crash to `LoopRotate::rotateLoop`,     │
│ specifically during the `verifyMemorySSA` call at the end of │
│ the function. This confirms that the `LoopRotate`            │
│ transformation itself is the source of the invalid MemorySSA │
│ state.\n- The log shows `LoopRotation: rotating Loop at      │
│ depth 1...`. This tells us which loop is being               │
│ transformed.\n- The IR has a complex, nested loop structure  │
│ with multiple exits and constant branches, which often       │
│ exposes edge cases in loop transformations. The presence of  │
│ `.us` suffixes in block names in the debug log (e.g.,        │
│ `%for.body.us`) indicates that `simple-loop-unswitch` has    │
│ already run, further complicating the CFG that `LoopRotate`  │
│ has to process.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nBy          │
│ inspecting the `LoopRotate` implementation                   │
│ (`llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopRotationUtils.cpp`), we can  │
│ trace the logic for updating MemorySSA. The `LoopRotate`     │
│ pass uses a `MemorySSAUpdater` to manage these               │
│ updates.\n\nThe key steps in `rotateLoop` are:\n1.  Create   │
│ new blocks for the rotated loop structure (`NewHeader`,      │
│ `NewPreheader`).\n2.  Move instructions from the original    │
│ header to the new blocks.\n3.  Update PHI nodes in the       │
│ original loop header's successors.\n4.  Update analyses,     │
│ including MemorySSA.\n\nThe problem lies in the MemorySSA    │
│ update logic. When `LoopRotate` moves instructions and       │
│ remaps operands, it must also update the corresponding       │
│ `MemoryAccess`es. The existing code correctly updates        │
│ `MemoryDef`s and `MemoryUse`s associated with moved          │
│ instructions. However, it overlooks a critical case:         │
│ updating the defining access for `MemoryPhi` nodes.\n\nWhen  │
│ the original loop header is duplicated, a `MemoryPhi` node   │
│ in a successor block might have an incoming value from the   │
