│ trace the logic for updating MemorySSA. The `LoopRotate`     │
│ pass uses a `MemorySSAUpdater` to manage these               │
│ updates.\n\nThe key steps in `rotateLoop` are:\n1.  Create   │
│ new blocks for the rotated loop structure (`NewHeader`,      │
│ `NewPreheader`).\n2.  Move instructions from the original    │
│ header to the new blocks.\n3.  Update PHI nodes in the       │
│ original loop header's successors.\n4.  Update analyses,     │
│ including MemorySSA.\n\nThe problem lies in the MemorySSA    │
│ update logic. When `LoopRotate` moves instructions and       │
│ remaps operands, it must also update the corresponding       │
│ `MemoryAccess`es. The existing code correctly updates        │
│ `MemoryDef`s and `MemoryUse`s associated with moved          │
│ instructions. However, it overlooks a critical case:         │
│ updating the defining access for `MemoryPhi` nodes.\n\nWhen  │
│ the original loop header is duplicated, a `MemoryPhi` node   │
│ in a successor block might have an incoming value from the   │
│ original header. After rotation, this path might now         │
│ originate from the *new* pre-header. The `MemoryPhi` needs   │
│ to be updated to reflect that its incoming definition now    │
│ comes from a different block and potentially a different     │
│ `MemoryAccess`.\n\nThe existing code in `rotateLoop` lacks a │
│ mechanism to explicitly find and update these `MemoryPhi`    │
│ nodes. The `MemorySSAUpdater`'s `moveInstruction` function   │
│ handles the moved instructions themselves, but it doesn't    │
│ automatically propagate this change to the PHI nodes that    │
│ use the results of the moved instructions. This omission     │
│ leads to a `MemoryPhi` in a successor block still referring  │
│ to a `MemoryDef` from the original header block, which,      │
│ after rotation, no longer dominates the successor, causing   │
│ the verification to fail.\n\nThe fix is to explicitly        │
│ iterate through the successors of the original loop header   │
│ after the main CFG changes have been made. For each          │
│ successor, we check its `MemoryPhi` nodes. If a `MemoryPhi`  │
│ has an incoming value from the original header, we update it │
│ to point to the correct new predecessor block                │
│ (`NewPreheader`) and the corresponding                       │
│ `MemoryAccess`.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix  │
│ involves adding code to `LoopRotate::rotateLoop` in          │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopRotationUtils.cpp` to handle  │
│ the `MemoryPhi` updates.\n\n```cpp\n//                       │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopRotationUtils.cpp\n\n// ...    │
│ inside LoopRotate::rotateLoop, after updating PHIs and       │
│ before verification ...\n\n  // Update MemorySSA.\n  if      │
│ (MSSA) {\n    // ... (existing MSSA update code) ...\n\n     │
│ // After moving the instructions, update the MemoryPHI nodes │
│ in the\n    // successors of the original header.\n    for   │
│ (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(OrigHeader)) {\n      if      │
│ (auto *MP = MSSA->getMemoryAccess(Succ)) {\n        if (auto │
│ *Phi = dyn_cast<MemoryPhi>(MP)) {\n          if              │
│ (Phi->getBlock() != Succ)\n            continue;\n           │
│ int BBIdx = Phi->getBasicBlockIndex(OrigHeader);\n           │
│ if (BBIdx != -1) {\n            Phi->setIncomingBlock(BBIdx, │
│ NewPreheader);\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    }\n     │
│ }\n\n  if (VerifyMemorySSA)\n                                │
│ MSSA->verifyMemorySSA();\n\n// ...\n```\n\nThis patch        │
│ iterates through the successors of the original header. For  │
│ each successor, it retrieves the `MemoryPhi` (if one exists  │
│ at the beginning of the block). It then checks if this       │
│ `MemoryPhi` has an incoming edge from the `OrigHeader`. If   │
│ so, it updates that incoming edge to come from the           │
│ `NewPreheader`, which is the correct new predecessor after   │
│ rotation."                                                   │
│ }                                                            │
